ce:section.ce:para:
Since hexaammineruthenium(III) chloride complex is well-documented as an outer-sphere redox probe sensitive to electron state density [28] but not to surface chemistry of the electrode surface, it was used to evaluate the relationship between edges and basal planes for spherical random carbon core (CND), stacked graphitic sheets forming a sphere (CQD) and individual single sheet (GQD) electrode. According to diverse authors [8,28], the A and electron transfer rates for Ru complex do not change from the surface chemistry but upon the electrode's electronic structure (Fermi levels and density of states), here mainly depending of ratio edge plane sites and defects. The analysis of voltammetric profiles assessed upon this redox probe was mainly based on the heterogeneous electron transfer rate constant (k

                           0’
                        ) and electroactive area (A) values, since the results in terms of potential difference (ΔE

                           p
                        ) have not provided relevant information; in fact similar values were achieved, namely 179, 173 y 172 mV for CND/Nf, CQD/Nf and GQD/Nf electrodes respectively. In terms of rate-limiting step (diffusion and/or adsorption), both processes were evaluated by representing the peak currents against the scan rate and the square root of scan rate. Results suggested that the kinetic of the electrochemical process at the CND/Nf, CQD/Nf and GQD/Nf electrodes are mainly controlled by the diffusion of electroactive species through the electrode surface owing to a linearly peak current dependency with the square root of scan rate. Considering k0’, calculated by Nicholson method [31], CND/Nf electrode displays the better rate-limiting step with a value 7.5·10−4 cm·s−1 followed by the GQD/Nf electrode with 5.3·10−4 cm·s−1. Since these voltammetric responses correlates with the proportion of edge and basal planes, it can be deduced that content of edges plane and defects plane is higher for the CND/Nf electrode whilst CQD/Nf and GQD/Nf electrodes have higher contents of basal plane which is consistent with their graphitized nanosheet-containing cores. Regarding the electroactive area (A), calculated with such near-ideal outer-sphere probe by the Randles-Sevcik equation [33], the CND/Nf modified electrode gave the best results too, followed by the GQD/Nf one (Table 1).
